Lazyux is a ultra-minimalistic, embedded-like Linux (https://www.kernel.org/)
distribution in its early stages of development.

TODO:
  - Persistency, using aufs3 (http://aufs.sourceforge.net/)
  - Built-in firewall
  - A kernel build script
  - A bootable media construction script, with UEFI support
  - More applications
  - Simple package management
  - More applets in lazy-utils, so some packages can be dropped

Features:
  - Free
  - Extremely lightweight
  - The whole thing is cross-compiled quickly
  - Everything is linked statically
  - Secure (WIP)

Potantial uses:
  - A "live" operating system for private browsing, system rescue, etc'
  - Firmware for routers, firewalls and switches
  - A dedicated server operating system

Included packages:
  - Core:
    - Linux (https://www.kernel.org/)
    - musl (http://www.musl-libc.org/)
    - toybox (http://www.landley.net/toybox/)
    - lazy-utils (https://github.com/iguleder/lazy-utils)
    - dash (http://gondor.apana.org.au/~herbert/dash/)
    - kmod (https://www.kernel.org/pub/linux/utils/kernel/kmod/)
    - eudev (https://github.com/gentoo/eudev)
    - ISC DHCP (http://www.isc.org/downloads/dhcp/)
  - Applications:
    - tcsh (http://www.tcsh.org/)
    - Lynx (http://lynx.isc.org/)
    - ircII (http://www.eterna.com.au/ircii/)
    - Dropbear (https://matt.ucc.asn.au/dropbear/dropbear.html)
    - vile (http://invisible-island.net/vile/)
    - GNU nano (http://www.nano-editor.org/)
    - Calcurse (http://calcurse.org/)
    - GNU Screen (http://www.gnu.org/software/screen/)
    - less (http://www.greenwoodsoftware.com/less/)
    - man (http://primates.ximian.com/~flucifredi/man/)
    - htop (http://htop.sourceforge.net/)
    - ncdu (http://dev.yorhel.nl/ncdu)
    - alsa-utils (www.alsa-project.org/)
    - mpg123 (http://www.mpg123.de/)
    - vorbis-tools (http://www.vorbis.com/)
    - bwm-ng (http://www.gropp.org/?id=projects&sub=bwm-ng)

While these packages are licensed under various licenses, Lazyux itself is
licensed under a 2-clause BSD license, see COPYING for the license text. For a
list of its authors and contributors, see AUTHORS.

The ASCII art logo at the top was made using FIGlet (http://www.figlet.org/).
